The investigation into the PI3K/Akt signaling pathway and p53 expression aimed to unravel the downstream effects of HPV16 E6 T350G overexpression on cellular signaling and tumor suppressor pathways. Dysregulation of the PI3K/Akt pathway and p53 expression has been implicated in cervical cancer progression, suggesting their potential involvement in HPV-mediated carcinogenesis. By assessing the phosphorylation levels of PI3K and Akt and quantifying p53 expression levels following HPV16 E6 T350G infection, we sought to elucidate the molecular mechanisms underlying the oncogenic properties of this viral mutation. Western Blot results revealed an upregulation of phosphorylated levels of PI3K and Akt in human cervical epithelial cells expressing HPV16 E6 T350G (P < 0.05), indicating potential activation of the PI3K/Akt signaling pathway by HPV16 E6 T350G via BDNF. Additionally, Real-time PCR experimental results demonstrated a significant decrease in p53 expression levels upon upregulation of HPV16 E6 T350G (P < 0.05), as shown in Table 4.Table 4
